8-Day Southbound Itinerary (Davenport Gap Start)

Night 0 (May 17): Arrive / camp or stay near Davenport Gap / Big Creek area (not in park yet). Drop one car at Fontana Dam the day before or arrange self-shuttle.
Day 1: May 18 – Davenport Gap to Cosby Knob Shelter (~7–8 miles)
Short, manageable first day with a solid climb. Allows time to settle into the rhythm and enjoy the initial forest.
Shelter: Cosby Knob Shelter (sleeps 12, often has a privy nearby).
Elevation notes: Steady climb with some views building.
Day 2: May 19 – Cosby Knob Shelter to Tricorner Knob Shelter (~9–10 miles)
Continues through high-elevation spruce-fir forest. Great section with potential for vistas.
Shelter: Tricorner Knob Shelter.
Highlights: Some of the most remote and beautiful ridgeline walking in the northern Smokies.
Day 3: May 20 – Tricorner Knob Shelter to Mt. Collins Shelter (~10–11 miles)
Passes near Pecks Corner area and approaches the Newfound Gap zone. Expect more foot traffic near roads.
Shelter: Mt. Collins Shelter (popular due to proximity to Newfound Gap).
Note: This day has some bigger ups/downs; water sources are generally reliable.
Day 4: May 21 – Mt. Collins Shelter to Derrick Knob Shelter (~11–12 miles)
Crosses Clingmans Dome area (highest point on the entire AT at 6,643 ft — side trail ~0.5 mile if you want the tower view). Then rolls through the central Smokies.
Shelter: Derrick Knob Shelter.
Highlights: Kuwohi (Clingmans Dome), possible panoramic views if weather cooperates. This is one of the tougher days elevation-wise.
Day 5: May 22 – Derrick Knob Shelter to Spence Field / Russell Field area (~10–11 miles)
Continues the rollercoaster with open balds and meadows.
Shelter options: Spence Field Shelter or Russell Field Shelter (both good stops; choose based on availability — Spence often preferred for views).
Highlights: Beautiful grassy areas and wildflowers in May.
Day 6: May 23 – Spence Field / Russell Field to Mollies Ridge Shelter (~9–10 miles)
Descending trend toward the western side of the park.
Shelter: Mollies Ridge Shelter.
Note: Nice transition day with some easier stretches mixed in.
Day 7: May 24 – Mollies Ridge Shelter to Birch Spring Gap or near Fontana approach (~10 miles)
Final big push through lower elevations.
Shelter / site: Birch Spring Gap campsite or a shelter near the western end (some itineraries use Russell Field again or adjust). Many hikers push toward the dam area here.
Day 8: May 25–26 – Final push to Fontana Dam (~8–10 miles remaining)
Descend to Fontana Dam (the "Fontana Hilton" area is just outside the park). Finish early on Day 8 or buffer an extra day if needed. Pick up your second car.

Total: ~72 miles over 8 hiking days / 7 nights inside the park. This gives a comfortable buffer for weather, fatigue, or slower days in the steep sections.


Here's a **detailed elevation profile** for the **8-day / 7-night southbound itinerary** (Davenport Gap → Fontana Dam, May 18–26, 2026). Distances are approximate (based on standard AT Data Book, NPS, and trail measurements; total ~71–72 miles with ~17,000–20,000 ft cumulative gain for the full traverse, depending on exact routing and GPS vs. wheel measurements). The "Smoky Mountain Roll" means frequent steep ups and downs even on "easier" days.

I've included:
- **Day-by-day mileage** (from previous sample)
- **Starting/ending shelter elevations**
- **Approximate daily elevation gain/loss** (net change shown; actual "rollercoaster" effort is higher due to multiple climbs/descents)
- **Key high/low points and notes** (including major features like Clingmans Dome/Kuwohi)

### Day 1: May 18 – Davenport Gap to Cosby Knob Shelter (~7–8 miles)
- **Start**: Davenport Gap (~1,975–2,000 ft)
- **End**: Cosby Knob Shelter (~4,700–4,740 ft)
- **Elevation Gain**: ~2,800–3,000 ft
- **Elevation Loss**: ~300–500 ft
- **Net**: Significant climb overall
- **Key notes**: Steady initial climb through forest. Lower elevations feel milder in May. Water usually available near shelter. Good "warm-up" day with building views.

### Day 2: May 19 – Cosby Knob Shelter to Tricorner Knob Shelter (~9–10 miles)
- **Start**: Cosby Knob Shelter (~4,740 ft)
- **End**: Tricorner Knob Shelter (~5,920 ft)
- **Elevation Gain**: ~2,200–2,500 ft
- **Elevation Loss**: ~1,000–1,200 ft
- **Net**: Moderate net gain
- **Key notes**: High-elevation spruce-fir forest. Passes near Mt. Cammerer side trail (optional steep climb to fire tower). Some of the most remote feeling ridgeline in the northern Smokies. Potential for cooler temps and wind.

### Day 3: May 20 – Tricorner Knob Shelter to Mt. Collins Shelter (~10–11 miles)
- **Start**: Tricorner Knob Shelter (~5,920 ft)
- **End**: Mt. Collins Shelter (~5,870–5,962 ft)
- **Elevation Gain**: ~2,000–2,400 ft
- **Elevation Loss**: ~2,000–2,300 ft
- **Net**: Near neutral (lots of rolling)
- **Key notes**: Approaches the Newfound Gap area (more hikers possible). Crosses high ridges with occasional views. Water sources generally reliable. This section stays mostly above 5,000–6,000 ft.

### Day 4: May 21 – Mt. Collins Shelter to Derrick Knob Shelter (~11–12 miles)
- **Start**: Mt. Collins Shelter (~5,870 ft)
- **End**: Derrick Knob Shelter (~4,770–4,880 ft)
- **Elevation Gain**: ~2,500–3,000 ft (including climb to high point)
- **Elevation Loss**: ~3,500–4,000 ft
- **Net**: Net loss, but big effort
- **Key notes**: **Highlight day** — side trail to **Kuwohi (Clingmans Dome)** at 6,643 ft (highest point on the entire AT; ~0.5 mile round-trip if you detour for the tower/view). Significant rollercoaster with steep descents after the high point. Expect possible wind/rain at elevation. Since you've hiked this section before, you'll know the payoff views when clear.

### Day 5: May 22 – Derrick Knob Shelter to Spence Field / Russell Field Shelter (~10–11 miles)
- **Start**: Derrick Knob Shelter (~4,770 ft)
- **End**: Spence Field Shelter (~4,800–5,000 ft) or Russell Field Shelter (~4,500–4,800 ft; both similar area)
- **Elevation Gain**: ~2,800–3,200 ft
- **Elevation Loss**: ~2,500–2,800 ft
- **Net**: Slight net gain or neutral
- **Key notes**: Beautiful open balds and meadows (great for May wildflowers). Thunderhead Mountain and Rocky Top nearby (iconic views). Grassy areas make for nice breaks. Shelters here are popular — have backup options when booking.

### Day 6: May 23 – Spence Field / Russell Field to Mollies Ridge Shelter (~9–10 miles)
- **Start**: Spence/Russell Field area (~4,800 ft)
- **End**: Mollies Ridge Shelter (~4,570 ft)
- **Elevation Gain**: ~2,000–2,400 ft
- **Elevation Loss**: ~2,300–2,700 ft
- **Net**: Slight net loss
- **Key notes**: Transition toward the western Smokies. Some easier stretches mixed with steep rolls. Descending trend begins as you head toward lower elevations near Fontana.

### Day 7: May 24 – Mollies Ridge Shelter to Birch Spring Gap or western approach shelter/site (~10 miles)
- **Start**: Mollies Ridge Shelter (~4,570 ft)
- **End**: Birch Spring Gap (~3,680–3,800 ft) or nearby site
- **Elevation Gain**: ~1,800–2,200 ft
- **Elevation Loss**: ~2,600–3,000 ft
- **Net**: Net loss
- **Key notes**: More descending overall. Passes Doe Knob and other gaps. Water at Birch Spring Gap. Final big push through forested sections before the dam area.

### Day 8: May 25–26 – Final push to Fontana Dam (~8–10 miles remaining)
- **Start**: Birch Spring Gap area (~3,680 ft)
- **End**: Fontana Dam (~1,800–1,837 ft)
- **Elevation Gain**: ~1,000–1,500 ft (smaller rolls)
- **Elevation Loss**: ~2,800–3,200 ft
- **Net**: Major net descent
- **Key notes**: Steep final drop to the dam ("Fontana Hilton" just outside park boundary). Finish early enough to retrieve your car. Celebrate the traverse!

**Overall Trip Totals** (approximate for 72 miles southbound):
- **Cumulative Elevation Gain**: 17,000–20,000+ ft (classic "Smoky Mountain Roll" — relentless short steep climbs/descents average ~250–280 ft per mile)
- **Cumulative Elevation Loss**: Roughly equal to gain
- **Highest Point**: Kuwohi/Clingmans Dome (6,643 ft) on Day 4
- **Lowest Point**: Fontana Dam (~1,800 ft) at finish

### Additional Tips for Your Experienced Group
- **Pacing**: Days 4 and 5 are the most strenuous due to high elevation and big vertical. Since you've done Clingmans-to-Fontana before, you can fine-tune pacing there.
- **May Variables**: Expect mud, possible lingering snow/ice above 5,000 ft early in the trip, and afternoon thunderstorms. Start early on bigger days.
- **Water**: Most shelters have springs nearby, but always treat/filter. May is generally wetter, but dry stretches can occur.
- **Booking Note**: When reserving on smokiespermits.nps.gov (before April 29), input these exact shelter stops night-by-night. If a preferred shelter is taken, nearby alternatives (e.g., Russell Field vs. Spence Field) are often close enough to swap.

This profile gives a solid sense of the daily effort. The total vertical makes the Smokies one of the tougher sections on the AT despite "only" 72 miles.

If you'd like me to adjust for a **7-day faster version** (longer daily miles), add more granular mile-by-mile breakdowns for any specific day, include water source details, or compare with a northbound profile, just let me know your preferences or group pace! Safe planning and hiking.


Here's the information you need on **parking permits (called "parking tags")** for your **southbound Appalachian Trail traverse** through Great Smoky Mountains National Park (Davenport Gap / Big Creek area at the northeast end to Fontana Dam at the southwest end), May 18–26, 2026.

### Do You Need Parking Tags?
**Yes.**
Backcountry hikers and overnight users are **not exempt**. You must have a valid parking tag for each vehicle left at the trailheads for more than 15 minutes. This applies even if you're only parking overnight or for several days while hiking the 72-mile section.

- **NE end (start)**: Davenport Gap or Big Creek trailhead/parking area.
- **SW end (finish)**: Fontana Dam parking area.

You will leave one car at each end (self-shuttle setup), so **both vehicles** need their own parking tag while parked.

**Exceptions** (none of which likely apply here):
- Parked less than 15 minutes.
- Just driving through without stopping.
- Handicap license plate or placard.
- Certain free entrance days (parking tags are waived on those specific dates).

### Parking Tag Options and Costs (2026 rates)
These apply to **all vehicle sizes and types**:
- **Daily**: $5 (valid for 1 day, expires at 11:59 p.m. ET on the printed date)
- **Weekly**: $15 (valid for up to 7 days, expires at 11:59 p.m. ET on the printed date)
- **Annual**: $40 (good for a full year)

**Recommendation for your trip**:
A **weekly tag** ($15 per vehicle) should cover your ~8–9 day window easily. Buy two weekly tags (one for each car) if your parking periods overlap or to be safe. Tags are **not transferable** between vehicles — each must list the correct license plate.

Tags are **non-refundable**, **non-replaceable**, and **non-upgradable**. You must **print a physical paper copy** and display it on the **front lower passenger-side dashboard** of each vehicle (digital versions are not accepted).

### How and Where to Buy Parking Tags
**Best option — Buy in advance online** (recommended to avoid morning lines or issues at trailheads):
- Daily and weekly tags: https://www.recreation.gov/activitypass/AP2510 (available up to 6 months ahead).
- You’ll receive an email with the tag to print.

**In-person options** (if you prefer or need last-minute):
- Visitor centers (e.g., Sugarlands Visitor Center near Gatlinburg).
- Gatlinburg Welcome Center.
- Automated fee machines at several locations (credit card only, 24/7 at some spots like Big Creek, Cosby, etc.).
- Other stores and kiosks in/near the park.

**Note**: Most remote trailheads (including Davenport Gap/Big Creek and Fontana Dam) do **not** have kiosks, so online purchase is safest.

**Annual tags** are purchased separately through the Great Smoky Mountains Association (smokiesinformation.org or similar).

### Important Logistics for Your Setup
- **Parking is first-come, first-served** — A tag does **not** reserve or guarantee a spot. Arrive early at both trailheads, especially if dropping a car the day before your May 18 start.
- **Duration planning**: Time your tags to cover the full period each car will be parked (e.g., drop car at Fontana Dam a day early → start its tag then; same for the start vehicle).
- **Display correctly**: License plate number on the tag must match the vehicle.
- **Consequences of no tag**: Warning, citation, or towing at your expense.

### Official Resources
- **NPS Fees & Passes page** (most authoritative): https://www.nps.gov/grsm/planyourvisit/fees.htm
- **Recreation.gov Parking Tag purchase**: https://www.recreation.gov/activitypass/AP2510
- **Backcountry Camping page** (cross-references parking): https://www.nps.gov/grsm/planyourvisit/backcountry-camping.htm

Parking tags are completely separate from your **backcountry permits** (the shelter reservations you're booking on the old system next week). They serve different purposes and are purchased independently.

If you're coordinating two cars and want tips on drop-off timing, alternate parking areas, or anything else (like current conditions at Fontana Dam or Big Creek lots), just let me know your exact plan and I can help refine it. Good luck with booking everything!


Here's detailed information on **shelter availability** for your southbound 72-mile AT traverse through Great Smoky Mountains National Park (Davenport Gap to Fontana Dam, May 18–26, 2026), using the **General Backcountry Permit** (specific shelter reservations required each night).

### How Shelter Availability Works in GSMNP
- All overnight stays (including shelters) require advance reservations via your backcountry permit. You **must** reserve a **specific shelter** for each night of your itinerary — no first-come, first-served option for general permit holders like your group.
- **No consecutive nights** allowed at any shelter (or at certain campsites like #113). This prevents overuse and helps with your multi-day traverse.
- **Capacities**: Most AT shelters in the Smokies sleep 8–12 people on two-level wooden platforms (exact numbers vary; some are smaller). The park limits reservations per night based on capacity to avoid overcrowding. Your group size (if more than 1–2) will affect options — maximum party size is typically 8 without special approval.
- **General Permit vs. Thru-Hiker Permit**: With your General Backcountry Permit, you have priority for the bunks in your reserved shelter. Qualifying AT thru-hikers (with the special flat-fee permit) **must** stay in shelters if space is available but can tent nearby if full. They may be displaced by reserved parties like yours.
- **No tenting at shelters** for general permit holders (hammocks also cannot be attached to shelters). You stay inside your reserved shelter or move to a different reserved site.
- **May 2026 Timing**: Mid-to-late May is popular (spring wildflowers, milder weather before summer crowds/thunderstorms peak). Shelters near Newfound Gap / Clingmans Dome area and the central balds (e.g., Spence Field, Russell Field) tend to book faster, especially on weekends. Weekday nights may have better availability.

### Key AT Shelters on Your Southbound Route
Here are the primary shelters along the ~72-mile section (approximate order from NE to SW, with rough mile markers from Davenport Gap and typical elevations). These align with the 8-day sample itinerary:

- **Cosby Knob Shelter** (~7–8 miles in, ~4,700 ft) – Good first-night option; often quieter.
- **Tricorner Knob Shelter** (~16–18 miles, ~5,900 ft) – High-elevation, remote feel.
- **Mt. Collins Shelter** (~26–28 miles, ~5,900 ft) – Popular due to proximity to Newfound Gap road access; can fill on weekends.
- **Derrick Knob Shelter** (~37–39 miles, ~4,800 ft) – Near Clingmans Dome high point; high demand.
- **Spence Field Shelter** or **Russell Field Shelter** (~47–50 miles, ~4,500–4,900 ft) – Beautiful bald/meadow area; very popular in spring for views and wildflowers. These are close enough that one can often substitute for the other.
- **Mollies Ridge Shelter** (~57–59 miles, ~4,570 ft) – Western side transition.
- **Birch Spring Gap** (campsite/shelter area near end, ~3,700 ft) or other western options leading to Fontana Dam.

Other nearby options (for alternates): Double Spring Gap, Siler's Bald, or Pecks Corner (slightly off-route but sometimes usable with adjustments).

Most shelters have:
- Bear cables for food storage (mandatory — hang all odorous items).
- Nearby water sources (treat/filter all water).
- Privies (composting toilets).
- Fire rings (fires allowed only in rings with downed wood).

### Checking and Booking Availability
- **Right now (before April 29, 2026)**: Use the old system at **https://smokiespermits.nps.gov/**. You can search by date and build your exact night-by-night itinerary, seeing real-time availability for specific shelters. Book your full May 18 start as soon as possible — popular dates/shelters can go quickly.
- **After April 30, 2026**: Switch to **Recreation.gov** (https://www.recreation.gov/permits/4675347). The process is similar; availability will show when you select dates and sites.
- **Pro Tip**: Log in early (system opens for May dates in the 30-day window). Have 1–2 alternate shelters per night ready (e.g., swap Spence Field for Russell Field). If your preferred itinerary isn't fully available, the Backcountry Office can help adjust pacing.
- **No public "real-time" availability calendar** outside the booking systems — you must go through the permit site to see what's open.

### Backup Options if Preferred Shelters Are Taken
- Adjust daily mileage slightly to hit different shelters (your experienced group can handle flexible pacing).
- In rare cases, the Backcountry Office may suggest nearby campsites (still reserved in advance).
- Carry a lightweight tent/tarp as emergency backup (though not allowed at reserved shelters unless you're a qualifying thru-hiker).

### Contact for Help
Call the **Backcountry Office** at **865-436-1297** (8 a.m.–5 p.m. ET, Monday–Friday). They are very helpful for itinerary planning, checking current conditions, and advising on realistic shelter combinations for your pace. Mention your southbound 72-mile plan and approximate daily miles.

### Quick Reminders
- Print your paper permit with all shelter reservations listed.
- No changes after booking without calling the office.
- Bear activity is common — properly store food every night.
- May weather: Expect variable conditions (rain, mud, possible cool nights at elevation). Check updates closer to your trip.

Shelter reservations are the biggest planning piece for your trip, so booking soon on the old system gives you the best shot at your ideal stops. If you tell me your exact group size or preferred average daily mileage (e.g., 9–11 miles vs. more aggressive), I can suggest refined alternates or help prioritize certain shelters.

Let me know how booking goes or if you need more on water sources, bear cables, or anything else! Safe travels on the Smoky Mountain Roll.


